      "top-title": "THE DEVELOPMENT OF SYSTEMS FOR HELP AND GENERAL ASSISTANCE <span>.</span>",
      "top-message": `<p>What would a programmer be like if he couldn't abstract, use creativity and innovation with the desire to help each other?<br>A programmer, for me, is like a digital architect. He doesn't just write lines of code, he builds virtual worlds from scratch. This is someone who sees patterns where others see chaos, who turns complex problems into exciting challenges.<br>The magic is in the ability to abstract - it's like being able to see code as a language of its own and understand its dance. Creativity is the spark that makes each line unique, it is the personal touch that turns code into something more than a simple sequence of instructions. And innovation is the constant drive to improve, to seek new ways of doing things, to create something revolutionary from the conventional.<br>But what really drives many programmers, including me, is the idea of making a difference. It's knowing that each line of code can improve someone's life, simplify tasks, connect people or solve complex problems. It is the incessant search to help, to contribute to a world where technology is not just a tool, but a force for good.<br>So, being a programmer is not just about technical skills, but about a mix of passion, creativity and the desire to make a positive impact on the world.</p>`,
